5.  Finance and economics specialist (3.0 person-months). The consultant should have 
a master’s degree in finance, economics, or accounting, preferably with recognized professional 
accountancy qualification and professional membership (e.g., chartered accountant or certified 
public accountant) and 10 years experience in utility finance and economics. Proposed activities 
for this position are to 
(i)  assess the financial performance of past rural WSS projects; 
(ii)  identify  and  assess  sectoral  financial  management  issues  and  risks,  identify 
credible remedial measures, and support initial capacity development activities; 
(ii)  prepare and manage the willingness-to-pay survey; 
(iii)  conduct financial analysis of demonstration projects; and 
(iv)  prepare  asset  ownership  plan  and  tariff  and  subsidy  mechanism,  including 
methodology and formulas for tariff and subsidy calculations, review mechanism, 
adjustment mechanism, and tariff reset periods or events. 

6.  Key deliverables for this position are: 
(i)  inputs to the report on project lessons;  
(ii)  sector financial management assessment and action plan;  
(iii)  willingness-to-pay report; 
(iv)  inputs to the demonstration project assessment report;  
(v)  draft asset ownership plan; and 
(vi)  draft tariff and subsidy mechanism.  

7.  Water supply and sanitation engineer (6.0 person-months). The consultant should 
have a master’s degree in engineering with 15 years experience in WSS engineering. Proposed 
activities for this position are to 
(i)  conduct technical analysis of development partner projects;  
(ii)  lead  the  review  of  the  demonstration  projects  and  preparation  of  projects 
assessment report;  
(iii)  prepare the information gathering and benchmarking plan; 
(iv)  prepare and implement revised technical standards;  
(v)  prepare standardized design approaches and procurement plan; and 
(vi)  prepare and implement operation and maintenance guidelines.  

8.  Key deliverables for this position are: 
(i)  final report on project lessons;  
(ii)  final demonstration project assessment report;  
(iii)  draft rural WSS technical standards; 
(iv)  draft operation and maintenance guidelines implementation plan; 
(v)  draft standardized design approaches and procurement plan; and 
(vi)  draft information gathering and benchmarking plan. 

